{
  "query": "What are the observed effects of different agricultural water management practices, including effluent treatment and water source provision, on bat populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available studies, there are limited observations on the effects of agricultural water management practices on bat populations. For effluent treatments used in agriculture and forestry, no studies have evaluated their effects on bat populations (Action 1016). \n\nRegarding water source provision, several studies show positive effects on bat populations. Five replicated studies across Israel, USA, Germany, South Africa and Mexico found that bat activity was similar or higher over artificial water sources including reservoirs, waste water treatment pools, heliponds, drainage ditches, retention ponds, and farm/cattle ponds compared to natural wetlands or surrounding habitats like vineyards, forest, grassland, crops, trees and orchards (Action 959). One study in South Africa found similar numbers of bat species over farm ponds compared to surrounding agricultural areas (Action 959).\n\nFor livestock water management, two studies in the USA evaluated livestock water troughs as drinking resources for bats. One study found that removing livestock modifications from water troughs resulted in bats drinking from them more frequently and approaching troughs fewer times before successfully drinking (Action 1951). Another study found that larger livestock water tanks that were full of water or surrounded by sparse vegetation had more bats drinking from them than smaller, half-full tanks surrounded by no vegetation or dense vegetation (Action 1951).\n\nSmall dams for water provision also showed positive effects, with one study in Portugal finding that reservoirs created using small dams had greater activity of four bat species than the streams feeding into them (Action 1997).",
  "action_ids": [
