{
  "query": "To mitigate road impacts on bats, how effective are different purpose-built crossing structures like green bridges, overpasses, and gantries?",
  "relevant_summary": "The effectiveness of purpose-built crossing structures for mitigating road impacts on bats varies significantly by structure type. Green bridges show the highest effectiveness, with one study in the UK finding that a green bridge was used by 97% of bats crossing a road (Action 979). Overpasses show mixed effectiveness depending on design features. Three studies in Europe and Australia found that two or three bat species/species groups used overpasses, but up to three-quarters of bats still crossed the road below at traffic height or at other nearby locations (Action 977). However, design matters significantly - one study in the UK found that an overpass with planters was used by two-thirds of crossing bats, while an unvegetated overpass with a paved road over it was not used by crossing bats at all (Action 977). One study in Australia found that the same number of bat species were recorded at an overpass as in nearby forest and bushland (Action 977). Bat gantries or bat bridges appear to be the least effective option. Three studies in the UK and France found that fewer bats used bat gantries than crossed the road below at traffic height, with one bat gantry not being used at all (Action 978). In France, a temporary bat gantry was used by three bat species/species groups, but almost half of crossing bats flew over the road at other locations (Action 978).",
