{
  "query": "What design and placement factors are associated with higher occupancy rates of artificial bat roosts?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on evidence from multiple studies, several design and placement factors are associated with higher occupancy rates of artificial bat roosts. Design factors include: black bat boxes had higher usage than grey, white or wooden boxes (Action 1024). Larger bat boxes had higher occupancy rates in one of two studies (Action 1024). Concrete bat boxes had higher occupancy rates than wooden ones (Action 1024). Bat boxes with two compartments had higher occupancy than single compartments during breeding season (Action 1024). Indiana bats preferred rocket boxes over wooden bat boxes or bark-mimic roosts (Action 1024). Bat boxes simulating tree trunks achieved 100% occupancy with group sizes similar to natural roosts (Action 1024). For placement factors: bat box orientation and amount of sunlight exposure affected occupancy in three studies (Action 1024). Bat box height affected occupancy in two studies (Action 1024). Bat boxes on buildings had higher occupancy than those on trees in two studies (Action 1024). Higher occupancy was found in farm forestry sites compared to native forest, and in pine stands compared to mixed deciduous stands (Action 1024). Areas where bats were previously known to roost had higher occupancy rates (Action 1024). Installing a greater number of bat boxes across a site increased likelihood of occupancy (Action 1024). Temperature management also matters, as artificial roosts modified to reduce internal temperatures had increased bat numbers (Action 2052).",
