{"query": "What conservation actions can be implemented to mitigate the impacts of mining operations on bats?", "summary": "Several conservation actions can be implemented to mitigate the impacts of mining operations on bats, though scientific evidence for their effectiveness varies. Installing and maintaining gates at mine entrances to restrict public access has been studied in nine studies across the USA and Australia (Action 1963). These studies found that gates can reduce the number of bat species entering mines and result in fewer bats at mine entrances, though bat activity remained stable or increased at five of seven gated mines. Gate design and installation timing affect success, with some bats abandoning mines with 'ladder' design gates, and up to 7% of bats colliding with mine gates.

Maintaining microclimate in closed/abandoned mines can be beneficial, with one USA study finding that modifying the microclimate by closing a man-made entrance resulted in greater numbers of bats hibernating within the mine (Action 1964). Other proposed actions include excluding bats from roosts prior to mine reclamation (Action 1961), retaining access points for bats following mine closures (Action 1962), reopening entrances to closed mines and making them suitable for roosting bats (Action 1965), providing artificial subterranean bat roosts to replace roosts in reclaimed mines (Action 974), and relocating bats from reclaimed mines to alternative subterranean roost sites (Action 975), though no studies have evaluated the effectiveness of these latter actions.

Artificial caves or hibernacula can be created as replacement habitat, with studies from the UK and Germany showing that artificial hibernacula are used by up to four bat species and that bat use can increase over time (Action 2049). However, many mining-specific mitigation strategies lack scientific evaluation of their effectiveness on bat populations.", "action_ids": ["1961","1962","1963","1964","1965","974","975","2049"]}
